\section org_mitk_views_m2_docker_metabolicdepthOverview Overview

The Metabolic Depth plugin applies the Multi-GASTON (MET-MAP) method to learn metabolic depth (isodepth) from mass spectrometry imaging data. This technique uses a neural network to identify and quantify spatial gradients in metabolite abundance patterns, revealing underlying tissue organization and metabolic zonation.

Multi-GASTON is particularly useful for analyzing tissue structures with known spatial organization, such as:
- Liver zonation (portal to central vein gradients)
- Kidney nephron segments
- Intestinal crypt-villus axis
- Tumor microenvironment gradients

\section org_mitk_views_m2_docker_metabolicdepthRequirements Requirements

This plugin requires:
- Docker installed and running on your system
- The metabolic depth Docker image: \c ghcr.io/m2aia/metabolicdepth:latest
- A spectrum image (MSI data)
- A centroid list defining metabolites of interest
- (Optional) A segmentation mask to restrict analysis to specific regions

\section org_mitk_views_m2_docker_metabolicdepthUsage Usage

\subsection org_mitk_views_m2_docker_metabolicdepthInput Input Selection

1. <b>Spectrum Image:</b> Select the mass spectrometry imaging dataset
2. <b>Centroid List:</b> Select the list of metabolite m/z values to analyze
3. <b>Mask (Optional):</b> Select a segmentation to restrict analysis to specific tissue regions
4. <b>Mask Label (Optional):</b> If using a multi-label segmentation, select the specific label to analyze

\subsection org_mitk_views_m2_docker_metabolicdepthParameters Algorithm Parameters

- <b>Number of Isodepths (K):</b> Number of distinct spatial gradients expected in the data (typically 1 for tissues with one dominant gradient like liver)
- <b>Training Epochs:</b> Number of iterations for neural network training (12,000 is a good default; increase for more complex patterns)
- <b>Number of Restarts:</b> Number of random initializations (10 recommended; the best model is selected automatically)
- <b>Mass Tolerance (ppm):</b> Tolerance for extracting ion images (typically 75 ppm)

\subsection org_mitk_views_m2_docker_metabolicdepthOutput Output

The plugin generates a metabolic depth image showing the learned spatial gradient(s). Higher values indicate greater metabolic depth along the learned axis. For liver tissue, this typically represents the portal-to-central vein axis.

The output image can be:
- Visualized as a heatmap overlay on the original MSI data
- Used for downstream analysis (e.g., correlating gene expression or metabolite levels with zonation)
- Exported for further processing or publication

\section org_mitk_views_m2_docker_metabolicdepthReferences References

Multi-GASTON: Metabolic-Tissue-depth Analysis via Spatial Transcriptomics Or Metabolomics
- GitHub: https://github.com/raphael-group/Multi-GASTON

\section org_mitk_views_m2_docker_metabolicdepthTips Tips and Best Practices

- <b>Crop Selection:</b> For large images, consider cropping to focus on specific tissue regions with clear spatial organization
- <b>Training Time:</b> Training can take several minutes to hours depending on image size and number of restarts
- <b>Multiple Restarts:</b> Using 10 restarts helps ensure the neural network finds a good solution despite random initialization
- <b>Validation:</b> Compare the learned isodepth with known marker metabolites to validate the results
*/
